description:
In the Term::Halt lowering inside compile_fn (ir_codegen.rs), the native branch
computes `val` and then immediately discards it:

  Term::Halt(v) => {
      let val = *var_map.get(&v.0).expect("unbound halt val");
      if is_native {
          // ...
          let _ = return_reprs[this_spec_id as usize];
          let zero = b.ins().iconst(types::I64, 0);
          b.ins().return_(&[zero]);
          let _ = val;   // <-- val discarded
      } else {
          let null = b.ins().iconst(types::I64, 0);
          b.ins().return_(&[null]);
      }
  }

The value is never used in the native branch (fz_halt is no-return at runtime;
the returned bits are unobservable). Remove the `val` binding from the native
branch entirely. The uniform branch doesn't use `val` either, so the lookup
can be removed from both.

The let binding should move inside the else branch only if the uniform path
needs it, or be removed entirely if neither path uses it after the refactor.
Verify by reading the code: if uniform also discards val, remove the binding
from both.

Proven: existing fixture tests pass unchanged.

